# AGENTS.md — repo contract for the review-loop agents

> Copy this file to the ROOT of any target repo the `review-loop` orchestrator
> works in, and fill in the project-specific commands. Both `claude_code` and
> `codex` read it; `claude_code` also picks it up via the `@AGENTS.md` include in
> `CLAUDE.md` (see CLAUDE.md.snippet).

## Build / test / lint commands

<!-- Fill these in for THIS project. Examples: -->
- Install:   `<e.g. uv sync  |  npm ci  |  pip install -e .>`
- Test:      `<e.g. pytest -q  |  npm test>`
- Lint:      `<e.g. ruff check .  |  npm run lint>`
- Typecheck: `<e.g. mypy .  |  npm run typecheck>`

An implementer must drive the code it touched to **green** on test + lint +
typecheck before opening its PR.

## Definition of done

- The scoped task is complete and all gates above pass.
- The change is the **smallest diff** that satisfies the acceptance contract —
  no drive-by refactors or scope creep.
- New behavior has tests; changed behavior updates them.
- The PR description says **what** changed and **how it was verified**.

## Hard rules

- **Nobody merges or pushes to a protected branch but the human.** Implementers
  open a PR on a task branch and stop. The orchestrator never merges. Reviewers
  never edit — they only report findings.
- **No force-push, no `rm -rf /`, no hard-reset to a remote ref** (enforced by
  the `blast_radius` policy, but treat it as a rule, not just a guardrail).
- Stay strictly within the files/scope named in the task and this contract.
- Co-sign every commit with the trailer the worker prompts already require:
  `Co-authored-by: omnigent <noreply@omnigent.ai>`.

## Methodology

Superpowers is active in both CLIs — follow it: brainstorm → spec → plan →
TDD → inline self-review during the build. Cross-vendor review happens *after*
the in-family self-review, as a second pair of eyes.
